                 <h2>Why second is nowhere for Liverpool Football Club</h2>
                              <img src = "26.jpg" Width="500" Height="300" style="border:thick double #300000"/>

                              <p style="color:white;text-align:left">
                              
                              It is one of the Bill Shankly's best  known quotations, 
'If you are first you are first. If you are second you are nothing',
and while it isn't the most famous shanklyism, it is one that perhaps holds the most weight currently for his old club.
<br></br>
Steven Gerrard's cruel slip against Chelsea ended Liverpool's magical run in and wrenched control of the title out of the Anfield clubs hands.
<br></br>
It was a kick aimed and landed squarely in the Liverpool squads gut, it hurt them then, and it is hurting them now.
<br></br>
Fast forward 5 months and the ramifications of the final few games are apparent, gone is the mercurial Luis Suarez, sold to Barcelona, also lost is the vibrancy and attacking verve which became the Liverpool hallmark in the previous campaign.
<br></br>
Arguably Liverpool's only perfect performance came in the capital against a fragile and evolving Spurs side under new manager Mauricio Pocchetino.
The rest on the whole has made for uncomfortable viewing.
<br></br>
Questions have been asked of the manager, of his tactics defensively, his spending in the summer broke through the 100m mark and the reality that so far none of his signings have made a substantial impact.
<br></br>
The season is yet young but improvement must come soon or the vital champions league positions may evade Liverpool come May.
That would prove a major problem for Liverpool, their supporters and their owners, FSG in Boston.
<br></br>
Anything other than top four would be seen as major setback, and of Brendan Rodgers a more serious question would perhaps have to be asked.
<br></br>
Modern football can be notoriously fickle, a couple of good results against Madrid and Chelsea and it could be all smiles on Merseyside again, well on one half at least.
                          
                              </p>
                              

